arch:property.oc:show_val: Later accumulation of debris and fill following the collapse of the cryptoporticus vault and of the colonnade architecture.
Phase XII: Robbing and abandonment continue.
Phase XI: Further collapse post-CE 5th c. Possibly the result of the earthquake of CE 512.

Locus 1 is a thick layer of fine, silt like soil (Munsell 7.5 YR 4/6, Strong Brown) with a heavy concentration of large and small stones, including a substantial amount of architectural fragments. It extends across the entire trench. Most notable are the large number of column drums and elephant-headed capital fragments, many of which are in particularly good condition. This locus was distinguishable also for its relative lack of pottery (either wares or roof tiles) and tesserae, when compared with the highest soil locus in Trench 69 directly to the east. Its initial surface sloped downward rapidly from the northwest edge of the Lower Temenos. This locus represents the collapse of the north end of the West Triple Colonnade and the later accumulation mixed in with it.
Phase XIII: Major collapses continue into the Islamic period.
